                                        "type": "text",
                                        "assets": [],
                                        "textTypeData": {
                                            "html": "<p>About 1,000 thousand schoolchildren were among the many who marched to St Peter’s Square for the unveiling, chanting “<a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2018/jun/10/women-march-across-uk-to-celebrate-100-years-of-female-suffrage\">deeds not words</a>” as the bronze sculpture was revealed.</p> \n<p>Beforehand, they danced to Sisters Are Doin’ It For Themselves by Aretha Franklin and Annie Lennox and waved homemade banners. One had felt-tipped “I would rather be a rebel than a slave”, one of Pankhurst’s most famous sayings, and surrounded it with red hearts.</p> \n<p>Metrolink, which runs Manchester’s busy tram system, agreed to pause the trams through the square during the event, to ensure the warning horn did not ruin the moment. Earlier, 94-year-old Nancy Sawyer had volunteered to chain herself to the railings to stop the trams from disturbing the ceremony.</p>"
                                        }
